Step 3: Simplify the Right-Hand Side of the Equation
The expanded form of $(1-\sqrt{1-x^2})^2$ is:
\begin{align*}
(1-\sqrt{1-x^2})^2&amp;={1^2-2\cdot1\cdot\sqrt{1-x^2}+(\sqrt{1-x^2})^2}\\
&amp;=1-2\sqrt{1-x^2}+(1-x^2)
\end{align*}

Step 1: Cross-multiply
To eliminate the fractions, we cross-multiply:
\begin{align*}
    (5x+1)(2x-1)&=(2x)(2x^2+5x-3)
\end{align*}

Step 2: Distribute and Expand
Distribute and expand both sides:
\begin{align*}
    10x^2 - 5x + 2x - 1 &= 4x^3 + 10x^2 - 6x\\
    10x^2 - 3x - 1 &= 4x^3 + 10x^2 - 6x
\end{align*}

Step 5: Solve for $x$.
Setting each factor equal to zero yields,
$
\begin{array}{c|cccccc}
x&amp;\hspace{.125in}-\frac53&amp; 1&amp;\\
\cline{1-3}
&amp;\hspace{.125in} - \frac 13&amp;&\frac 23&amp;
\\[7pt]
\hline
        \end{array}

\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{5}{3} = x \text{   or }\boxed{\boxed{x = 1}}

Step 6: Solve the Quadratic Inequality
The quadratic inequality  is now $ 4x^2 - 7x - 1 = 0 $, which cannot be solved by factorization. To find its solutions, use the quadratic formula:
$$ x =  rac{-b ± sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a} $$ Here  a=4,b=-7,c=-1 The discriminant \sqrt{b^2 – 4ac} in this case is \sqrt{(-7)^2–(4 * 4 * (-1))}=sqrt{49+16}=sqrt{65}. Thus, x is given by \begin{align*}x &amp;= rac{-(-7)±\sqrt{65}}{2(4)} \\&amp;=\frac{7±\sqrt{65}}{8}\end{align*}

